{
  "document_id": "prov-26",
  "title": "Proverbs 26",
  "type": "study-bible",
  "translation": "Oxford",
  "blocks": [
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-heading-27",
      "type": "heading",
      "text": "27"
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-2",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 2,
      "text": "Like a sparrow in its flitting, like a swallow in its flying, an undeserved curse goes nowhere."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-3",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 3,
      "text": "A whip for the horse, a bridle for the donkey, and a rod for the back of fools."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-h1kj-4",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "3 : , see 10.13n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 26
      },
      "verse_start": 3,
      "verse_end": 3
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-4",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 4,
      "text": "Do not answer fools according to their folly, or you will be a fool yourself."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-5",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 5,
      "text": "Answer fools according to their folly, or they will be wise in their own eyes."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-h1kj-5",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "4–5 : Contradictory proverbs about whether to speak to fools. The wise must discern which proverb is appropriate in a given circumstance (e.g., 15.23; 25.11).",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 26
      },
      "verse_start": 4,
      "verse_end": 5
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-6",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 6,
      "text": "It is like cutting off one's foot and drinking down violence, to send a message by a fool."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-h1kj-6",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "6 : , see 13.17n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 26
      },
      "verse_start": 6,
      "verse_end": 6
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-7",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 7,
      "text": "The legs of a disabled person hang limp; so does a proverb in the mouth of a fool."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-8",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 8,
      "text": "It is like binding a stone in a sling to give honor to a fool."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-9",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 9,
      "text": "Like a thornbush brandished by the hand of a drunkard is a proverb in the mouth of a fool."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-10",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 10,
      "text": "Like an archer who wounds everybody is one who hires a passing fool or drunkard."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-11",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 11,
      "text": "Like a dog that returns to its vomit is a fool who reverts to his folly."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-h1kj-7",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "11 : , regarded in the ancient Near East as a dirty scavenger; ancient Israelites did not commonly domesticate dogs (e.g., 26.17; 1 Kings 21.19,23–24; Eccl 9.4; but see Job 30.1).",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 26
      },
      "verse_start": 11,
      "verse_end": 11
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-12",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 12,
      "text": "Do you see persons wise in their own eyes? There is more hope for fools than for them."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-h1kj-2",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "26.1–12 : Proverbs about fools.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 26
      },
      "verse_start": 1,
      "verse_end": 12
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-h1kj-8",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "12 : , see 3.7n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 26
      },
      "verse_start": 12,
      "verse_end": 12
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-13",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 13,
      "text": "The lazy person says, “There is a lion in the road! There is a lion in the streets!”"
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-h1kj-10",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "13 : See 22.13.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 26
      },
      "verse_start": 13,
      "verse_end": 13
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-14",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 14,
      "text": "As a door turns on its hinges, so does a lazy person in bed."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-15",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 15,
      "text": "The lazy person buries a hand in the dish, and is too tired to bring it back to the mouth."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-h1kj-11",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "15 : See 19.24.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 26
      },
      "verse_start": 15,
      "verse_end": 15
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-16",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 16,
      "text": "The lazy person is wiser in self-esteem than seven who can answer discreetly."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-h1kj-9",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "13–16 : The lazy person (see 6.9–11n.).",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 26
      },
      "verse_start": 13,
      "verse_end": 16
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-h1kj-12",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "16 : , a round number signifying many (e.g., 6.16–19; 24.16).",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 26
      },
      "verse_start": 16,
      "verse_end": 16
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-17",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 17,
      "text": "Like somebody who takes a passing dog by the ears is one who meddles in the quarrel of another."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-h1kj-14",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "17 : , see v.11n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 26
      },
      "verse_start": 17,
      "verse_end": 17
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-18",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 18,
      "text": "Like a maniac who shoots deadly firebrands and arrows,"
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-19",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 19,
      "text": "so is one who deceives a neighbor and says, “I am only joking!”"
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-h1kj-15",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "18–19 : (i.e., deadly darts). Deception as a weapon, see 25.18.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 26
      },
      "verse_start": 18,
      "verse_end": 19
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-20",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 20,
      "text": "For lack of wood the fire goes out, and where there is no whisperer, quarreling ceases."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-21",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 21,
      "text": "As charcoal is to hot embers and wood to fire, so is a quarrelsome person for kindling strife."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-22",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 22,
      "text": "The words of a whisperer are like delicious morsels; they go down into the inner parts of the body."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-h1kj-16",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "20–22 : , a metaphor for conflict.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 26
      },
      "verse_start": 20,
      "verse_end": 22
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-h1kj-17",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "22 : See 18.8n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 26
      },
      "verse_start": 22,
      "verse_end": 22
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-23",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 23,
      "text": "Like the glaze covering an earthen vessel are smooth lips with an evil heart."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-h1kj-19",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "23 : , lit., “silver of dross,” a cheap coating that makes a vessel appear attractive and valuable, but actually cheapens and weakens it. , lit., “burning”; see v. 18.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 26
      },
      "verse_start": 23,
      "verse_end": 23
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-24",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 24,
      "text": "An enemy dissembles in speaking while harboring deceit within;"
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-25",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 25,
      "text": "when an enemy speaks graciously, do not believe it, for there are seven abominations concealed within;"
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-h1kj-18",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "23–25 : False friends.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 26
      },
      "verse_start": 23,
      "verse_end": 25
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-26",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 26,
      "text": "though hatred is covered with guile, the enemy's wickedness will be exposed in the assembly."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-27",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 27,
      "text": "Whoever digs a pit will fall into it, and a stone will come back on the one who starts it rolling."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-h1kj-20",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "27 : See Eccl 10.8–9; Sir 27.25–27.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 26
      },
      "verse_start": 27,
      "verse_end": 27
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-28",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 28,
      "text": "A lying tongue hates its victims, and a flattering mouth works ruin."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-h1kj-1",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "25.1–29.27: These are other proverbs of Solomon that the officials of King Hezekiah of Judah copied.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 26
      },
      "verse_start": 1,
      "verse_end": 28
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-26-h1kj-13",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "17–28 : Proverbs about various troublemakers.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 26
      },
      "verse_start": 17,
      "verse_end": 28
    }
  ]
}